I want you to watch this 'cause
I don't want to have to do it again.

1377
01:13:37,622 --> 01:13:40,457
I'll make myself about six
or seven inches shorter, okay?

1378
01:13:40,457 --> 01:13:43,385
- It's about right. Maybe a little more.
- Okay. A little more.

1379
01:13:51,385 --> 01:13:53,385
That's not funny.

1380
01:13:55,890 --> 01:13:59,394
Now, nobody's hurt. Right?

1381
01:14:00,394 --> 01:14:02,394
Right. Nobody hurt.

1382
01:14:05,649 --> 01:14:10,529
Now, this is the way I'd stab a man
who was taller than I was.

1383
01:14:10,529 --> 01:14:12,073
Look at the angle - down and in.

1384
01:14:13,073 --> 01:14:15,073
And this is the way it was done.

1385
01:14:15,243 --> 01:14:17,243
Now tell me I'm wrong.

1386
01:14:19,622 --> 01:14:23,126
- Down and in. I guess there's no argument.
- Hold it a minute, will ya?

1387
01:14:23,126 --> 01:14:24,126
Can you give me that?

1388
01:14:25,962 --> 01:14:27,962
Boy, I hate these things.

1389
01:14:27,963 --> 01:14:29,715
- Did you ever see a knife fight?
- No.

1390
01:14:29,715 --> 01:14:31,384
- You?
- No.

1391
01:14:31,384 --> 01:14:34,261
Anybody here ever see a knife fight?

1392
01:14:34,261 --> 01:14:37,140
Well, I have.
You know, on my back stoop...

1393
01:14:37,140 --> 01:14:39,140
the lot across the street, backyard.

1394
01:14:39,559 --> 01:14:41,060
Switchblades came
with the neighborhood where I lived.

1395
01:14:42,060 --> 01:14:45,060
It's funny I never thought of it before.
I guess you try to forget those things.

1396
01:14:45,398 --> 01:14:48,398
- How do you use a switchblade?
- Well, you'd never use it like this.

1397
01:14:50,528 --> 01:14:52,528
See, you use too much time
switching hands.

1398
01:14:54,573 --> 01:14:57,573
Here's how - underhanded.

1399
01:14:59,787 --> 01:15:02,787
Anyone who's ever used a switch knife
wouldn't handle it any other way.

1400
01:15:02,914 --> 01:15:05,626
- Are you sure?
- I'm sure.

1401
01:15:05,626 --> 01:15:07,545
That's why they're made to open like that.

1402
01:15:07,545 --> 01:15:10,256
- You'd say the boy was pretty handy with a knife?
- Mm-hmm.

1403
01:15:10,256 --> 01:15:13,256
You think he could have made
the kind of wound that killed his father?

1404
01:15:13,509 --> 01:15:17,509
No. Not with the experience he'd had
all his life handling these things.

1405
01:15:17,512 --> 01:15:19,512
I feel he'd have gone for him underhanded.

1406
01:15:19,599 --> 01:15:22,599
How do you know? Were you
in the room when the father was killed?

1407
01:15:22,726 --> 01:15:24,726
No. Neither was anybody else.

1408
01:15:24,811 --> 01:15:28,106
So what are you giving us all this
mumbo jumbo for? I don't believe it.

1409
01:15:28,106 --> 01:15:31,106
I don't think you can determine what type of
wound the boy might or might not have made...

1410
01:15:31,444 --> 01:15:34,154
simply because he knew
how to handle a knife.

1411
01:15:34,154 --> 01:15:36,154
What do you think?

1412
01:15:36,573 --> 01:15:38,573
- I don't know.
- What do you mean you don't know?

1413
01:15:38,743 --> 01:15:40,743
I don't know.

1414
01:15:44,789 --> 01:15:46,789
How about you?

1415
01:15:46,876 --> 01:15:50,712
I don't know about the rest of them, but I'm getting a
little tired of this yackety-yackin' back and forth.

1416
01:15:50,712 --> 01:15:54,257
It's gettin' us nowhere.
So I guess I'll have to break it up.

1417
01:15:54,257 --> 01:15:56,257
I change my vote to not guilty.

1418
01:15:56,886 --> 01:16:00,305
- You what?
- You heard me. I've had enough.

1419
01:16:00,305 --> 01:16:02,305
What do you mean you've had enough?
That's no answer!

1420
01:16:02,850 --> 01:16:06,850
Hey, listen. You just take care
of yourself, huh? You know?

1421
01:16:06,895 --> 01:16:10,895
He's right. That's not an answer.

1422
01:16:10,942 --> 01:16:13,942
What kind of a man are you?

1423
01:16:13,985 --> 01:16:17,198
You have sat here and voted guilty
with everyone else...

1424
01:16:17,198 --> 01:16:21,198
because there are some baseball tickets
burning a hole in your pocket.

1425
01:16:21,534 --> 01:16:25,534
And now you've changed your vote because you
say you're sick of all the talking here?

1426
01:16:26,791 --> 01:16:28,333
Now listen, buddy!

1427
01:16:28,333 --> 01:16:33,088
Who tells you that you have the right
to play like this with a man's life?

1428
01:16:33,088 --> 01:16:35,088
- Don't you care -
- Now wait a minute!

1429
01:16:35,675 --> 01:16:39,675
- You can't talk like that to me!
- I can talk like that to you.

1430
01:16:39,761 --> 01:16:41,721
If you want to vote not guilty...

1431
01:16:41,721 --> 01:16:44,182
then do it because you are convinced
the man is not guilty...

1432
01:16:44,182 --> 01:16:45,060
not because you've had enough.

1433
01:16:46,060 --> 01:16:48,060
And if you think he is guilty,
then vote that way.

1434
01:16:48,729 --> 01:16:51,024
Or don't you have the guts
to do what you think is right?

1435
01:16:52,024 --> 01:16:54,024
- Now listen.
- Guilty or not guilty?

1436
01:16:55,069 --> 01:16:58,069
- I told you, not guilty.
- Why?

1437
01:17:00,323 --> 01:17:01,033
Look, I don't have to...

1438
01:17:02,033 --> 01:17:05,033
You do have to! Say it! Why?

1439
01:17:05,246 --> 01:17:07,216
All right. I don't, uh, think he's guilty.

1440
01:17:17,216 --> 01:17:18,216
I want another vote.

1441
01:17:18,926 --> 01:17:21,511
Okay. There's another vote called for.

1442
01:17:21,511 --> 01:17:24,472
I guess the quickest way is a show of hands.
Anyone object?

1443
01:17:24,472 --> 01:17:27,310
Okay. All those voting not guilty,
raise your hands.

1444
01:17:28,310 --> 01:17:33,310
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven...

1445
01:17:36,319 --> 01:17:37,319
eight.

1446
01:17:41,907 --> 01:17:44,036
Um, nine.

1447
01:17:45,036 --> 01:17:50,036
Um, all those voting guilty,
raise your hands.

1448
01:17:50,123 --> 01:17:52,123
One, two, three.

1449
01:17:52,585 --> 01:17:55,087
Well, the vote's nine to three
in favor of acquittal.

1450
01:17:56,087 --> 01:17:58,087
I don't understand you people!

1451
01:17:58,341 --> 01:18:00,341
I mean, all these picky little points
you keep bringing up.

1452
01:18:00,592 --> 01:18:03,012
They don't mean nothing!
You saw this kid just like I did.

1453
01:18:04,012 --> 01:18:07,012
You're not gonna tell me you believe
that phony story about losing the knife...

1454
01:18:07,600 --> 01:18:09,600
and that business
about being at the movies.

1455
01:18:09,685 --> 01:18:12,685
Look, you know how these people lie.
It's born in them.

1456
01:18:12,771 --> 01:18:14,771
I mean, what the heck.
I don't have to tell you.

1457
01:18:14,899 --> 01:18:16,899
They don't know what the truth is.

1458
01:18:16,942 --> 01:18:20,738
And let me tell you, they don't need
any real big reason to kill someone either.

1459
01:18:20,738 --> 01:18:22,573
No, sir.

1460
01:18:22,573 --> 01:18:25,573
They get drunk!
Oh, they're real big drinkers, all of 'em.

1461
01:18:25,701 --> 01:18:28,701
You know that.
And bang - someone's lying in the gutter.

1462
01:18:28,953 --> 01:18:31,041
Well, nobody's blaming them for it.
That's the way they are, by nature.

1463
01:18:32,041 --> 01:18:34,041
You know what I mean? Violent!

1464
01:18:34,210 --> 01:18:35,210
Where are you going?

1465
01:18:35,795 --> 01:18:38,795
Î—uman life don't mean
as much to them as it does to us.

1466
01:18:39,798 --> 01:18:42,798
Look! They're lushing it up
and fighting all the time...

1467
01:18:42,885 --> 01:18:44,885
and if somebody gets killed,
so somebody gets killed!

1468
01:18:44,970 --> 01:18:46,430
They don't care!

1469
01:18:46,430 --> 01:18:48,430
Oh, sure, there's some good things
about 'em too.

1470
01:18:48,724 --> 01:18:50,724
Look, I'm the first one to say that.

1471
01:18:50,768 --> 01:18:54,145
I've known a couple who were okay, but
that's the exception, you know what I mean?

1472
01:18:54,145 --> 01:18:57,145
Most of 'em, it's like they have no feelings.
They can do anything.

1473
01:18:57,983 --> 01:19:00,653
What's going on here?

1474
01:19:00,653 --> 01:19:02,653
I'm - I'm trying to tell ya...

1475
01:19:02,779 --> 01:19:04,779
you're making a big mistake, you people.

1476
01:19:04,864 --> 01:19:07,578
This kid is a liar!
I know it. I know all about them.

1477
01:19:09,578 --> 01:19:11,578
Listen to me.
They're no good.

1478
01:19:11,831 --> 01:19:14,210
There's not a one of 'em who's any good.

1479
01:19:16,210 --> 01:19:18,210
I mean, what -
What's happening in here?

1480
01:19:18,753 --> 01:19:21,216
I'm speaking my piece, and you...

1481
01:19:22,216 --> 01:19:23,216
Listen to me.

1482
01:19:24,969 --> 01:19:26,511
I...

1483
01:19:26,511 --> 01:19:28,055
We're - This kid on trial here, his type...

1484
01:19:29,055 --> 01:19:31,018
Well, don't you know about them?

1485
01:19:33,018 --> 01:19:36,018
Th-There's - There's a danger here.

1486
01:19:36,564 --> 01:19:38,564
These people are dangerous.

1487
01:19:38,731 --> 01:19:41,731
They're... wild.

1488
01:19:41,860 --> 01:19:43,860
Listen to me.

1489
01:19:43,863 --> 01:19:46,282
- Listen.
- I have.

1490
01:19:46,282 --> 01:19:49,204
Now sit down
and don't open your mouth again.

1491
01:19:53,204 --> 01:19:55,204
I was only trying to... tell you.

1492
01:20:32,453 --> 01:20:36,453
It's always difficult to keep personal
prejudice out of a thing like this.

1493
01:20:37,875 --> 01:20:41,463
Wherever you run into it,
prejudice always obscures the truth.

1494
01:20:43,463 --> 01:20:45,463
I don't really know what the truth is.

1495
01:20:45,925 --> 01:20:48,136
I don't suppose anybody
will ever really know.

1496
01:20:50,136 --> 01:20:54,136
Nine of us now seem to feel
that the defendant is innocent.

1497
01:20:54,182 --> 01:20:57,182
But we're just gambling on probabilities.

1498
01:20:57,269 --> 01:20:59,269
We may be wrong.

1499
01:20:59,313 --> 01:21:01,313
We may be trying to let
a guilty man go free.

1500
01:21:01,774 --> 01:21:03,317
I don't know.

1501
01:21:03,317 --> 01:21:05,317
Nobody really can.

1502
01:21:05,402 --> 01:21:07,402
But we have a reasonable doubt...

1503
01:21:07,863 --> 01:21:11,449
and that's something
that's very valuable in our system.

1504
01:21:11,449 --> 01:21:15,449
No jury can declare a man guilty
unless it's sure.

1505
01:21:17,456 --> 01:21:19,456
We nine can't understand...

1506
01:21:19,917 --> 01:21:22,462
how you three are still so sure.

1507
01:21:23,462 --> 01:21:25,462
- Maybe you can tell us.
- I'll try.

1508
01:21:26,840 --> 01:21:30,426
You've made some excellent points, but I
still believe the boy is guilty of murder...

1509
01:21:30,426 --> 01:21:32,220
and I have two reasons.

1510
01:21:32,220 --> 01:21:35,220
One, the evidence
given by the woman across the street...

1511
01:21:35,431 --> 01:21:38,143
who actually saw the murder committed.

1512
01:21:38,143 --> 01:21:40,143
As far as I'm concerned,
that's the most important testimony.

1513
01:21:40,813 --> 01:21:44,149
And two, the fact that she
described the stabbing by saying...

1514
01:21:44,149 --> 01:21:49,149
she saw the boy raise his arm over his head
and stab down into the father's chest.

1515
01:21:49,863 --> 01:21:51,863
She saw him do it the wrong way.

1516
01:21:51,990 --> 01:21:53,990
That's absolutely right.

1517
01:21:53,993 --> 01:21:56,662
Let's talk about this woman for a moment.

1518
01:21:56,662 --> 01:21:59,662
She said she went to bed
about 11:00 that night.

1519
01:21:59,832 --> 01:22:03,502
Her bed was next to the window,
and she could look out while lying down...

1520
01:22:03,502 --> 01:22:07,502
and see directly into the boy's room
across the street.

1521
01:22:07,672 --> 01:22:10,384
She tossed and turned for over an hour,
unable to sleep.

1522
01:22:10,384 --> 01:22:14,384
Finally, she turned toward the window
at about 10 minutes after 12:00...

1523
01:22:14,637 --> 01:22:19,637
and, as she looked out, she saw the killing
through the windows of a passing el train.

1524
01:22:19,851 --> 01:22:22,645
She said the lights went out
immediately after the killing...

1525
01:22:22,645 --> 01:22:27,444
but that she got a good look at the boy
in the act of stabbing his father.

1526
01:22:28,444 --> 01:22:32,032
As far as I can see it,
this is unshakable testimony.

1527
01:22:33,032 --> 01:22:35,032
- Well, that's the whole case.
- What do you think?

1528
01:22:41,081 --> 01:22:42,081
How about you?

1529
01:22:44,376 --> 01:22:46,376
I-I don't know.

1530
01:22:46,920 --> 01:22:48,006
So much evidence to sift.

1531
01:22:49,006 --> 01:22:50,006
This is a pretty complicated business.

1532
01:22:51,050 --> 01:22:54,050
Frankly, I don't see
how you can vote for acquittal.

1533
01:22:54,927 --> 01:22:57,347
It's not so easy to arrange
all the evidence in order.

1534
01:22:57,347 --> 01:22:59,347
You can throw out
all the other evidence!

1535
01:22:59,475 --> 01:23:03,145
The woman saw him do it!
What else do you want?

1536
01:23:03,145 --> 01:23:05,104
- Yeah, well, maybe -
- Let's vote on it.

1537
01:23:05,104 --> 01:23:07,104
Okay. There's another vote called for.

1538
01:23:07,358 --> 01:23:09,275
Anybody object?

1539
01:23:09,275 --> 01:23:12,275
All right. I'm changing my vote.
He's guilty.

1540
01:23:12,404 --> 01:23:14,404
Anybody else?
The vote is eight to four.

1541
01:23:14,907 --> 01:23:18,577
Why is this such a personal triumph
for you - this one vote?

1542
01:23:18,577 --> 01:23:22,122
Okay. I say we're a hung jury.
I say we take it in to the judge.

1543
01:23:22,122 --> 01:23:24,122
Î—ow about it?
I want to hear arguments.

1544
01:23:24,917 --> 01:23:27,671
You, you're the leader of the cause.
What about it?

1545
01:23:29,671 --> 01:23:31,590
Let's go over it again.

1546
01:23:31,590 --> 01:23:33,590
We've been over it again!

1547
01:23:33,591 --> 01:23:38,471
The boy in the gray flannel suit here is bouncin'
backwards and forwards like a tennis ball.

1548
01:23:38,471 --> 01:23:42,269
No point in getting nasty
and trying to turn this into a contest.

1549
01:23:44,269 --> 01:23:45,269
Okay.

1550
01:23:45,813 --> 01:23:48,813
Maybe we can talk about
setting some kind of time limit.

1551
01:23:48,940 --> 01:23:51,777
Yeah, once around for the deal, huh?

1552
01:23:51,777 --> 01:23:55,613
It's a quarter after 6:00.

1553
01:23:55,613 --> 01:23:57,613
Someone before mentioned 7:00.

1554
01:23:57,658 --> 01:24:00,118
I think that's a point at which
we might begin to discuss...

1555
01:24:00,118 --> 01:24:03,118
the question of whether
we're a hung jury or not.

1556
01:24:03,454 --> 01:24:05,454
Don't you feel well?

1557
01:24:06,457 --> 01:24:08,457
I feel perfectly well, thank you.

1558
01:24:08,502 --> 01:24:11,296
I was saying that 7:00
would be a reasonable time.

1559
01:24:11,296 --> 01:24:14,296
Uh, the reason I asked about that
was because, uh...

1560
01:24:14,298 --> 01:24:15,298
you were rubbing your nose like...

1561
01:24:15,967 --> 01:24:18,720
Oh, I'm sorry for interrupting...

1562
01:24:18,720 --> 01:24:21,015
but you made a gesture
that reminded me of something.

1563
01:24:22,015 --> 01:24:24,015
I'm trying to settle something here.
Do you mind?

1564
01:24:24,143 --> 01:24:26,143
Well, I think this is important.

1565
01:24:27,229 --> 01:24:29,105
Thank you.

1566
01:24:29,105 --> 01:24:31,105
Now then,
I'm sure you'll pardon me for this...

1567
01:24:31,817 --> 01:24:34,817
but I was wondering why
you were rubbing your nose like that.

1568
01:24:34,819 --> 01:24:36,572
Oh, come on, will ya?

1569
01:24:36,572 --> 01:24:40,572
At this point, I happen to be talking
to the gentleman sitting next to you!

1570
01:24:40,826 --> 01:24:44,162
Now, why were you rubbing
your nose like that?

1571
01:24:44,162 --> 01:24:48,162
Well, if it's any of your business, I was
rubbing it because it bothers me a little.

1572
01:24:48,332 --> 01:24:49,042
Oh. I'm sorry.

1573
01:24:50,042 --> 01:24:53,006
- Is it - Is it because of your eyeglasses?
- It is.

1574
01:24:54,006 --> 01:24:55,006
Now can we get on to something else?

1575
01:24:55,841 --> 01:25:00,511
Your eyeglasses made those two
deep impressions on the sides of your nose.

1576
01:25:00,511 --> 01:25:02,511
I hadn't noticed that before.

1577
01:25:02,765 --> 01:25:06,350
- That must be annoying.
- It is very annoying.

1578
01:25:06,350 --> 01:25:08,350
Well, I wouldn't know about that.

1579
01:25:08,353 --> 01:25:11,353
I've never worn eyeglasses.
Twenty-twenty.

1580
01:25:11,774 --> 01:25:14,235
Listen, will you come on already
with the optometrist bit?

1581
01:25:16,235 --> 01:25:19,235
The woman who testified
that she saw the killing...

1582
01:25:19,864 --> 01:25:23,411
had those same marks
on the sides of her nose.

1583
01:25:24,411 --> 01:25:26,411
Holy smokes! You know, he's right.

1584
01:25:26,704 --> 01:25:28,457
Please.

1585
01:25:28,457 --> 01:25:32,293
Just give me a minute,
and I'll be finished.

1586
01:25:32,293 --> 01:25:35,213
I don't know if anyone else
noticed that about her.

1587
01:25:35,213 --> 01:25:39,135
I didn't think of it then,
but I've been going over her face...

1588
01:25:40,135 --> 01:25:42,135
in my mind.

1589
01:25:42,345 --> 01:25:44,345
She had those same marks.

1590
01:25:45,349 --> 01:25:49,349
- She kept rubbing them in court.
- He's right. She did do that a lot.

1591
01:25:50,561 --> 01:25:55,317
This woman was about, uh -
about 45 years old.

1592
01:25:55,317 --> 01:25:59,317
She was making a tremendous effort
to look 35...

1593
01:25:59,363 --> 01:26:01,363
for her first public appearance.

1594
01:26:01,657 --> 01:26:04,657
Heavy makeup, dyed hair...

1595
01:26:04,993 --> 01:26:08,956
brand-new clothes that should have
been worn by a younger woman.

1596
01:26:08,956 --> 01:26:10,707
No glasses.

1597
01:26:10,707 --> 01:26:12,458
No, women do that.

1598
01:26:12,458 --> 01:26:14,458
See if you can get the
mental picture of it.

1599
01:26:14,962 --> 01:26:16,880
What do you mean, no glasses?

1600
01:26:16,880 --> 01:26:19,675
How do you know whether she wore glasses?
Just 'cause she was rubbing her nose?

1601
01:26:19,675 --> 01:26:21,675
Now, she had those marks. I saw 'em.

1602
01:26:21,969 --> 01:26:23,969
So what?
What do ya think that means?

1603
01:26:23,970 --> 01:26:27,265
- Listen, I'm getting so sick of your yelling in here!
- Come on. Forget it.

1604
01:26:27,265 --> 01:26:30,265
Hey, listen. Listen, he's right.
I saw them too.

1605
01:26:30,351 --> 01:26:33,351
I was the closest one to her. She had these,
uh - these things on the side of her nose.

1606
01:26:33,564 --> 01:26:36,564
- What do you call those on the side?
- Well, what point are you making here?

1607
01:26:36,859 --> 01:26:40,820
She had dyed hair, marks on her nose.
Well, what does that mean?

1608
01:26:40,820 --> 01:26:45,703
Could those marks be made
by anything other than eyeglasses?

1609
01:26:48,703 --> 01:26:51,122
No, they couldn't.

1610
01:26:51,122 --> 01:26:53,122
I didn't see any marks!

1611
01:26:54,751 --> 01:26:56,545
I did.

1612
01:26:56,545 --> 01:26:59,171
Strange, but I didn't
think about it before.

1613
01:26:59,171 --> 01:27:01,171
Well, what about the lawyer?
Why didn't he say something?

1614
01:27:01,382 --> 01:27:04,382
There are 12 people in here
concentrating on this case.

1615
01:27:04,386 --> 01:27:06,386
Eleven of us didn't think of it either.

1616
01:27:06,555 --> 01:27:09,555
Well, what about the district attorney?
Do you think he'd pull a trick like that?

1617
01:27:09,807 --> 01:27:11,807
Have her testify without her glasses?

1618
01:27:11,810 --> 01:27:15,810
Did you ever see a woman who had to wear glasses and
didn't want to because she thinks they spoil her looks?

1619
01:27:15,814 --> 01:27:19,400
Okay. She had marks on her nose.

1620
01:27:19,400 --> 01:27:23,154
I'm giving you that.
From glasses, right?

1621
01:27:23,154 --> 01:27:27,154
She didn't want to wear 'em out of the house
so people would think she's gorgeous.

1622
01:27:27,408 --> 01:27:31,079
But when she saw this kid killing his
father, she was in the house alone.

1623
01:27:32,079 --> 01:27:34,079
That's all.

1624
01:27:34,373 --> 01:27:38,087
- Do you wear glasses when you go to bed?
- No, I don't.

1625
01:27:40,087 --> 01:27:42,087
No one wears eyeglasses to bed.

1626
01:27:42,090 --> 01:27:45,090
It's logical to assume that she wasn't
wearing them when she was in bed...

1627
01:27:45,176 --> 01:27:46,011
tossing and turning, trying to fall asleep.

1628
01:27:47,011 --> 01:27:49,011
- How do you know?
- I don't know! I'm guessing.

1629
01:27:49,430 --> 01:27:51,430
I'm also guessing that she probably
didn't put her glasses on...

1630
01:27:51,975 --> 01:27:54,185
when she turned
to look casually out of the window.

1631
01:27:54,185 --> 01:27:56,021
And she herself testified the killing
took place just as she looked out.

1632
01:27:57,021 --> 01:28:00,021
The lights went off a split second later.
She couldn't have had time to put them on then.

1633
01:28:00,149 --> 01:28:01,149
- Wait a second.
- Here's another guess.

1634
01:28:01,859 --> 01:28:05,030
Maybe she honestly thought she saw the boy
kill his father. I say she only saw a blur.

1635
01:28:06,030 --> 01:28:09,030
How do you know what she saw?
How does he know all that?

1636
01:28:09,701 --> 01:28:12,537
How do you know what kind of glasses she wore?
Maybe they were sunglasses.

1637
01:28:12,537 --> 01:28:15,247
Maybe she was farsighted.
What do you know about it?

1638
01:28:15,247 --> 01:28:18,247
I only know the woman's eyesight
is in question now.

1639
01:28:18,585 --> 01:28:24,585
She had to be able to identify a person
60 feet away, at night, without glasses.

1640
01:28:24,800 --> 01:28:27,260
You can't send someone off to die
on evidence like that.

1641
01:28:27,260 --> 01:28:29,260
Oh, don't give me that.

1642
01:28:29,345 --> 01:28:31,345
Don't you think the woman
might have made a mistake?

1643
01:28:31,597 --> 01:28:34,100
- No.
- It's not possible?

1644
01:28:34,100 --> 01:28:35,100
No, it's not possible.

1645
01:28:38,689 --> 01:28:40,689
Is it possible?

1646
01:28:41,733 --> 01:28:43,572
Not guilty.

1647
01:28:47,572 --> 01:28:50,324
Do you think he's guilty?

1648
01:28:50,324 --> 01:28:52,079
I think he's guilty.

1649
01:28:55,079 --> 01:28:56,079
Do you?

1650
01:28:59,626 --> 01:29:02,626
No. I'm convinced.

1651
01:29:02,753 --> 01:29:04,422
Not guilty.

1652
01:29:04,422 --> 01:29:06,298
What's the matter with you?

1653
01:29:06,298 --> 01:29:08,298
I have a reasonable doubt now.

1654
01:29:08,301 --> 01:29:09,301
Eleven to one.

1655
01:29:09,927 --> 01:29:12,927
Well, what about all the other evidence?
What about all that stuff?

1656
01:29:12,930 --> 01:29:15,100
The knife, the whole business!

1657
01:29:15,100 --> 01:29:18,100
Well, you said we could throw out
all the other evidence.

1658
01:29:23,774 --> 01:29:25,774
Well, what do we do now?

1659
01:29:28,947 --> 01:29:30,698
You're alone.

1660
01:29:30,698 --> 01:29:34,698
I don't care whether I'm alone or not!
It's my right.

1661
01:29:37,706 --> 01:29:39,009
It's your right.

1662
01:29:49,009 --> 01:29:51,009
Well, what do you want?
I say he's guilty.

1663
01:29:53,055 --> 01:29:56,055
- We want to hear your arguments.
- I gave you my arguments.

1664
01:29:57,391 --> 01:29:59,391
We're not convinced.

1665
01:29:59,603 --> 01:30:02,480
We want to hear them again.

1666
01:30:02,480 --> 01:30:04,154
We have as much time as it takes.

1667
01:30:10,154 --> 01:30:14,154
Everything - Every single thing
that took place in that courtroom...

1668
01:30:14,701 --> 01:30:16,701
but I mean everything -
says he's guilty.

1669
01:30:16,703 --> 01:30:19,703
What do you think,
I'm an idiot or something?

1670
01:30:20,832 --> 01:30:22,001
Why don't you take that stuff
about the old man?

1671
01:30:23,001 --> 01:30:26,001
The old man who lived there
and heard everything.

1672
01:30:27,838 --> 01:30:29,591
Or this business about the knife.

1673
01:30:29,591 --> 01:30:31,591
What? 'Cause he found another one
exactly like it?

1674
01:30:31,676 --> 01:30:35,096
The old man saw him
right there on the stairs!

1675
01:30:35,096 --> 01:30:37,096
What's the difference
how many seconds it was?

1676
01:30:39,100 --> 01:30:41,100
Every single thing.

1677
01:30:42,520 --> 01:30:45,520
The knife falling through
a hole in his pocket.

1678
01:30:45,774 --> 01:30:49,194
You can't prove he didn't get to the door.

1679
01:30:49,194 --> 01:30:51,194
Sure, you can take all the time,
hobble around the room.

1680
01:30:51,695 --> 01:30:54,201
But you can't prove it!

1681
01:30:56,201 --> 01:30:59,201
And what about this business
of the el and the movies?

1682
01:30:59,912 --> 01:31:02,041
There's a phony deal
if I ever heard one.

1683
01:31:03,041 --> 01:31:07,041
I'll bet ya $5,000
I'd remember the movies I saw.

1684
01:31:07,337 --> 01:31:09,337
I'm telling ya,
everything that's gone on...

1685
01:31:09,672 --> 01:31:13,592
has been twisted and turned!

1686
01:31:13,592 --> 01:31:15,592
This business with the glasses?

1687
01:31:15,761 --> 01:31:21,393
How do you know she didn't have them on?
This woman testified in open court!

1688
01:31:21,393 --> 01:31:25,393
And what about hearing the kid yell, huh?

1689
01:31:25,438 --> 01:31:28,438
I'm telling ya, I've got
all the facts here.

1690
01:31:29,859 --> 01:31:31,113
Here. Ah...

1691
01:31:34,113 --> 01:31:36,113
Well, that's it!
That's the whole case.

1692
01:31:43,832 --> 01:31:45,711
Well?

1693
01:31:47,711 --> 01:31:49,711
Say something!

1694
01:31:54,842 --> 01:31:58,096
You lousy bunch of bleeding hearts.

1695
01:31:59,096 --> 01:32:01,096
You're not gonna intimidate me.

1696
01:32:01,099 --> 01:32:03,099
I'm entitled to my opinion.

1697
01:32:06,979 --> 01:32:11,113
Rotten kids.
You work your life out!

1698
01:32:16,113 --> 01:32:18,113
I can't keep...

1699
01:32:22,746 --> 01:32:24,292
No.

1700
01:32:28,292 --> 01:32:30,292
Not guilty.

1701
01:32:33,506 --> 01:32:35,177
Not guilty.

1702
01:32:38,177 --> 01:32:39,177
Not...

1703
01:32:50,356 --> 01:32:52,180
Um, we're ready now.

1704
01:34:46,180 --> 01:34:47,180
Hey!

1705
01:34:52,186 --> 01:34:53,186
What's your name?

1706
01:34:53,938 --> 01:34:55,523
Davis.

1707
01:34:55,523 --> 01:34:57,523
My name's McCardle.

1708
01:34:59,778 --> 01:35:01,529
Well, so long.

1709
01:35:01,529 --> 01:35:03,000
So long.


